Like many here, I quite enjoy and respect erudite use of language. But
I have been chided often by my daughter, one of whose degrees is in
Linguistics, for being too stuffy in my resistance to language
variance and usage. She points out that where I see laziness and
sloppy communication skills what I perhaps should be recognizing is
language evolution and what I should be asking is if those who raise
my ire are actually trying to communicate with *me*.

She's probably right about much of this. I suspect I lean too heavily
on the idea that there are standards by which those who speak and
write should be measured. But what I really can't stand (and what is
probably my main motivation in seeing her side of this) is that my
initial reactions betray a frustration that I once vowed I'd never
indulge, as in: &quot;You kids these days, with your _____.&quot;

Man I hate it when I'm my dad.

