Why shouldn't Cockneys be able to borrow a word if they feel like it?
Even if the word were Scots in origin, which sounds plausible, that's
no bar to it making its way into my family vocabulary.  We probably have
some Scots in the tree somewhere (one 'known' one being a pre-revolutionary
fellow on that grandmother's side of my tree).  Give a bit of language
conservatism and it makes its way down to me, a mere 2.5 centuries after
his immigration.

Even if we didn't have any Scots in our tree, we certainly have had
contact, and we have a history (at least back to this grandmother's
mother) of being word-acquisitive and -creative.

One the thing is, words make their way around with much greater
abandon than you'd ever guess by documents, or by assumptions of origins.
English speaking North Americans would be particularly good places to
find usages brought in to the language from disparate locales, and which
never made their way in to the Queen's English (whatever that winds up
being exactly).

A different one is, I think many families have usages that they seldom
use outside the family, but which are fairly common inside the group.
Certainly true of us.  While we're weird, I don't think this is a fundamental
weirdness (possibly we take it farther than most).  These words used
mostly inside the family may well show up in many families, but still
not enter written use, nor public speech.  So, while the word is
more or less common, it's invisible to dictionaries.

